{{Spanish name|'''Moya'''|'''Pons'''}}

Dr.&nbsp;'''Rafael Francisco “Frank” Moya Pons''' is one of the leading contemporary historians of the [[Dominican Republic]]. He has published many important books in the history and cultural heritage of the country.<ref>[http://histories.cambridge.org/credited_person?id=PonsFrank Cambridge University]</ref> One of his best-known works is ''Manual de historia dominicana'' (1992), now in its tenth edition which is a staple work of Dominican historiography. In 1985 he authored the book ''Between Slavery and Free Labor: The Spanish'', in 1998 ''The Dominican Republic: A National History''
and in 2007 ''	History of the Caribbean: plantations, trade, and war in the Atlantic world''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=chYbAAAAYAAJ&q=History+of+the+Caribbean:+plantations,+trade,+and+war+in+the+Atlantic+world&dq=History+of+the+Caribbean:+plantations,+trade,+and+war+in+the+Atlantic+world&cd=1 History of the Caribbean: plantations, trade, and war in the Atlantic world]</ref> He has also conducted much work into slavery in the Dominican Republic and Caribbean.

Moya has a Degree in 'Philosophy' at the [[Autonomous University of Santo Domingo]] (UASD); has a Master in both 'Latin American History' and 'European History' at [[Georgetown University]]. Moya has a Ph.D. in 'Latin American History', 'Economic Development' and 'Quantitative Methods' from [[Columbia University]].

Moya Pons has taught history at the [[Pontifical Catholic University Mother and Teacher]] in the Dominican Republic, in Columbia and [[University of Florida|Florida]] universities in the USA, and has been Research Professor at [[City College of New York|City College]].

Moya was President of the Dominican Academy of History. In 2013, he published ''Bibliografía de la Historia Dominicana 1730-2010''.

